istories -- tCanto XXXIII. Beatrice’s Prophecy, Matilda’s Name, and the Pilgrim’s Renewal -- tCONTRIBUTORS -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis new critical volume, the second to appear in the three-volume Lectura Dantis, contains expert, focused commentary on the Purgatorio by thirty-three international scholars, each of whom presents to the nonspecialist reader one of the cantos of the transitional middle cantica of Dante's unique Christian epic. The cast of characters is as colorful as before, although this time most of them are headed for salvation. The canto-by-canto commentary allows each contributor his or her individual voice and results in a deeper, richer awareness of Dante's timeless aspirations and achievements.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aItalian literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / General.2bisacsh  aallegory.  aavarice.  abeatrice.  acantos.  achristian epic.  achristianity.  adante.  adivine comedy.  adivine destiny.  aearthly paradise.  aenvy.  aethical choices.  aexcommunicates.  afree will.  agood vs evil.  ahuman love.  alectura dantis.  alove.  alust.  alute maker.  amount of purgatory.  apoetry and politics.  apurgatorio.  apurgatory.  areligion.  arepentance.  arevenge.  aritual.  asaints and sinners.  asalvation.  aseven deadly sins.  asloth.  asordello.  aspiritual growth.  aspiritual.  avalley of the rulers.  avirgil.1 aArmour, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCambon, Galuco, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCavallo, Jo Ann, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCervigni, Dino S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id